      <div id="about-col-2">
        How do we find up-to-the-minute information on almost every city in the world in just a click? Behind the scenes, worldview works with five APIs to pull detailed data about each city.

        <h2>Creating the Clock</h2>

        When you enter in a new city, the name is sent to <%= link_to 'Weather Underground', 'http://www.wunderground.com/weather/api/', target: '_blank' %>'s Autocomplete API, which matches your input with the most relevant city and returns its name, state, country and coordinates.<br><br>

        Next, this information is sent to <%= link_to 'Forecast.io', 'https://developer.forecast.io/', target: '_blank' %>, which returns the UTC Offset to generate that city's current time. With this information, worldview creates a new clock representing that city.

        <h2>Finding the Data</h2>

        With the city's clock created and saved to the database, the next step relies on you.<br><br>

        When you click the clock, all the information previously gathered is split up into separate API calls and sent out to <%= link_to 'The New York Times', 'http://developer.nytimes.com/docs', target: '_blank' %> for news; <%= link_to 'Forecast.io', 'https://developer.forecast.io/', target: '_blank' %> once again for the current weather; <%= link_to 'Flickr', 'https://www.flickr.com/services/api/', target: '_blank' %> for tagged photos; and <%= link_to 'Twitter', 'https://dev.twitter.com/', target: '_blank' %> for trending tweets carrying the city's hashtag.

        <h2>Instant Updates</h2>

        <%= link_to 'worldview','http://world-view.today' %> makes liberal use of AJAX (Asyncronous JavaScript and XML) calls to request and fetch data instantly. This allows the site to function on a single page for a truly seamless experience.<br><br>

